Installation

1) Python (FastAPI) prerequisites

- Install stripe-python (requirement: stripe-python >= 8.0):

  pip install "stripe>=8.0" fastapi uvicorn python-dotenv

  (This installs the Stripe Python SDK plus FastAPI and uvicorn; the stripe package on PyPI is the official SDK) [stripe - PyPI](https://pypi.org/project/stripe) [Set up your development environment - Stripe Documentation](https://docs.stripe.com/get-started/development-environment?lang=python).

2) Node / React prerequisites

- From your React project root, install the Stripe JS loader and the official React wrapper (use latest @stripe/stripe-js):

  npm install --save @stripe/react-stripe-js @stripe/stripe-js@latest

  or with yarn:

  yarn add @stripe/react-stripe-js @stripe/stripe-js

  (Official React Stripe.js setup commands) [React Stripe.js reference](https://stripe.com/docs/stripe-js/react) [Stripe.js reference](https://stripe.com/docs/js).

Environment variables (.env.example)

Create a .env file for your FastAPI server process (example shown below). Keep secret keys server-side only.

.env.example

```env
# .env.example for FastAPI + React integration

# Stripe publishable key (client-side)
STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=pk_test_your_publishable_key_here

# Stripe secret key (server-side)
STRIPE_SECRET_KEY=sk_test_your_secret_key_here

# Stripe webhook signing secret (for verifying webhook signatures)
STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET=whsec_your_webhook_secret_here

# Domain of your app (used for return_url and redirects)
DOMAIN=http://localhost:3000

# Static directory (optional, if serving client files via FastAPI)
STATIC_DIR=./static
```

(Exact env names and example are taken from Stripe samples and docs; keep secret keys off client code) [accept-a-payment sample .env example](https://github.com/stripe-samples/accept-a-payment/tree/main/payment-element) [Keys best practices](https://docs.stripe.com/keys-best-practices).

API keys: where to get them

- Generate publishable and secret keys in the Stripe Dashboard → Developers → API keys. Use the test keys for local/dev testing and swap to live keys in production [Stripe Dashboard — API keys](https://dashboard.stripe.com/test/apikeys) [Set up your development environment - Stripe Documentation](https://docs.stripe.com/get-started/development-environment?lang=python).

API Key & Security Best Practices (short, actionable)

- Never embed secret keys in client-side code or check them into VCS; publishable keys may be used in the browser [Keys best practices](https://docs.stripe.com/keys-best-practices).
- Store secrets in a secrets manager (AWS Secrets Manager, GCP Secret Manager, Azure Key Vault, HashiCorp Vault) or environment variables injected at runtime; avoid committing .env files to source control [Keys best practices](https://docs.stripe.com/keys-best-practices).
- Use restricted API keys when possible and apply least-privilege rules; rotate keys periodically and have a plan for rotation [Keys best practices](https://docs.stripe.com/keys-best-practices).
- Verify webhooks using the Stripe webhook signing secret; never trust payloads without verification [Webhooks documentation](https://docs.stripe.com/webhooks) [Configuring webhook endpoints](https://docs.stripe.com/webhooks/setup#configure-webhook-settings).

FastAPI Backend (complete example)

- Purpose: endpoints to create one-time PaymentIntent and to create a subscription (returning client secret for Payment Element), and webhook handler verifying Stripe signatures and handling payment_intent.succeeded and invoice.paid.

- Save as server/main.py (or main.py). This code is adapted to the Payment Element patterns from Stripe samples and demonstrates the required endpoints.

```python
# server/main.py
from fastapi import FastAPI, HTTPException, Request
from fastapi.responses import JSONResponse
from pydantic import BaseModel
import stripe
import os
import logging
from dotenv import load_dotenv

load_dotenv()

STRIPE_SECRET_KEY = os.getenv("STRIPE_SECRET_KEY")
STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET = os.getenv("STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET")
DOMAIN = os.getenv("DOMAIN", "http://localhost:3000")

if not STRIPE_SECRET_KEY:
    raise Exception("STRIPE_SECRET_KEY must be set in environment")

stripe.api_key = STRIPE_SECRET_KEY

app = FastAPI()
logging.basicConfig(level=logging.INFO)
logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)

class PaymentIntentRequest(BaseModel):
    amount: int  # amount in cents
    currency: str = "usd"

class SubscriptionRequest(BaseModel):
    price_id: str
    customer_email: str

@app.post("/create-payment-intent")
async def create_payment_intent(req: PaymentIntentRequest):
    try:
        intent = stripe.PaymentIntent.create(
            amount=req.amount,
            currency=req.currency,
            automatic_payment_methods={"enabled": True},
        )
        return {"client_secret": intent.client_secret}
    except Exception as e:
        logger.error(f"Error creating PaymentIntent: {e}")
        raise HTTPException(status_code=400, detail=str(e))

@app.post("/create-subscription")
async def create_subscription(req: SubscriptionRequest):
    try:
        # Create or reuse a Customer by email
        customers = stripe.Customer.list(email=req.customer_email, limit=1)
        if customers.data:
            customer = customers.data[0]
        else:
            customer = stripe.Customer.create(email=req.customer_email)

        # Create subscription in an incomplete state so we get the payment intent
        subscription = stripe.Subscription.create(
            customer=customer.id,
            items=[{"price": req.price_id}],
            payment_behavior='default_incomplete',
            expand=['latest_invoice.payment_intent'],
        )

        client_secret = subscription.latest_invoice.payment_intent.client_secret
        return {"client_secret": client_secret}
    except Exception as e:
        logger.error(f"Error creating subscription: {e}")
        raise HTTPException(status_code=400, detail=str(e))

@app.post("/webhook")
async def stripe_webhook(request: Request):
    payload = await request.body()
    sig_header = request.headers.get('stripe-signature')

    if not sig_header or not STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET:
        raise HTTPException(status_code=400, detail="Missing Stripe signature or webhook secret")

    try:
        event = stripe.Webhook.construct_event(
            payload=payload, sig_header=sig_header, secret=STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET
        )
    except stripe.error.SignatureVerificationError as e:
        logger.error(f"Webhook signature verification failed: {e}")
        raise HTTPException(status_code=400, detail="Invalid signature")
    except Exception as e:
        logger.error(f"Webhook error: {e}")
        raise HTTPException(status_code=400, detail="Webhook error")

    # Handle relevant events
    if event.type == 'payment_intent.succeeded':
        payment_intent = event.data.object
        logger.info(f"PaymentIntent succeeded: {payment_intent.id}")
        # TODO: mark order/receipt as paid in your DB

    elif event.type == 'invoice.paid':
        invoice = event.data.object
        logger.info(f"Invoice paid: {invoice.id} for subscription {invoice.subscription}")
        # TODO: grant access / mark subscription active in your DB

    else:
        logger.info(f"Unhandled event type: {event.type}")

    return JSONResponse(content={"status": "success"})

@app.get('/')
def root():
    return {"message": "Stripe FastAPI integration running"}
```

- Notes & references: This pattern (PaymentIntent creation + returning client_secret; subscription creation with payment intent via expand) follows Stripe Payment Element recommendations and Stripe sample code structure [accept-a-payment sample: server/python/main.py](https://github.com/stripe-samples/accept-a-payment/blob/main/payment-element/server/python/main.py) [Payment Element docs](https://docs.stripe.com/payments/payment-element) [Build subscriptions with Elements](https://docs.stripe.com/payments/advanced/build-subscriptions).

Serving the backend locally

- Run with uvicorn from project root:

  uvicorn server.main:app --reload --port 4242

(Use an appropriate port and set STRIPE_SECRET_KEY and STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET in your environment) [FastAPI docs].

React Frontend (complete example)

- Purpose: use Payment Element for both one-time payments and subscription initial payment flows. The frontend will:
  - Load Stripe with publishable key
  - Request client_secret from your backend (one-time PaymentIntent or subscription creation)
  - Render PaymentElement and confirm payment with stripe.confirmPayment

1) Minimal app initialization (App.jsx)

```jsx
// client/src/App.jsx
import React, {useEffect, useState} from 'react';
import {loadStripe} from '@stripe/stripe-js';
import {Elements} from '@stripe/react-stripe-js';
import CheckoutForm from './CheckoutForm';

const stripePromise = loadStripe(process.env.REACT_APP_STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY);

export default function App() {
  const [clientSecret, setClientSecret] = useState('');

  // Example: request client secret for a one-time payment
  useEffect(() => {
    fetch('/create-payment-intent', { method: 'POST', headers: {'Content-Type':'application/json'}, body: JSON.stringify({amount: 1400}) })
      .then(r => r.json())
      .then(data => setClientSecret(data.client_secret));
  }, []);

  const options = { clientSecret };

  return (
    <div>
      {clientSecret && (
        <Elements stripe={stripePromise} options={options}>
          <CheckoutForm />
        </Elements>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
```

- Note: If initiating a subscription, call your backend /create-subscription endpoint (POST with price_id and customer_email) to get the client_secret for the subscription's latest_invoice.payment_intent; then pass that client_secret to Elements initialization. This flow follows Stripe guidance for subscriptions with Payment Element [Build subscriptions with Elements](https://docs.stripe.com/payments/advanced/build-subscriptions) [React Stripe.js reference](https://stripe.com/docs/stripe-js/react).

2) Checkout form using PaymentElement (CheckoutForm.jsx)

```jsx
// client/src/CheckoutForm.jsx
import React, {useState} from 'react';
import {PaymentElement, useStripe, useElements} from '@stripe/react-stripe-js';

export default function CheckoutForm() {
  const stripe = useStripe();
  const elements = useElements();
  const [message, setMessage] = useState(null);
  const [isLoading, setIsLoading] = useState(false);

  const handleSubmit = async (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    if (!stripe || !elements) return;

    setIsLoading(true);

    const {error} = await stripe.confirmPayment({
      elements,
      confirmParams: {
        return_url: window.location.origin + '/order/complete',
      },
    });

    if (error) {
      // Show error to customer
      setMessage(error.message);
    } else {
      setMessage('Processing — you will be redirected');
    }

    setIsLoading(false);
  };

  return (
    <form id="payment-form" onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <PaymentElement />
      <button disabled={isLoading || !stripe || !elements}>
        {isLoading ? 'Processing...' : 'Pay now'}
      </button>
      {message && <div>{message}</div>}
    </form>
  );
}
```

- This front-end pattern matches Stripe’s Payment Element + React guidelines; confirmPayment is used to complete the PaymentIntent (or subscription initial invoice payment) created by the backend [React Stripe.js reference](https://stripe.com/docs/stripe-js/react) [Payment Element docs](https://docs.stripe.com/payments/payment-element).

Testing procedures (test mode, cards, webhooks)

1) Enable test mode & keys

- Use the test API keys from the Stripe Dashboard for all dev/test calls [Set up your development environment - Stripe Documentation](https://docs.stripe.com/get-started/development-environment?lang=python).

2) Test card numbers (common ones)

- Use these sample test cards in the PaymentElement during test mode (any future expiry date and any CVC):
  - Visa: 4242 4242 4242 4242
  - Visa (debit): 4000 0566 5566 5556
  - Mastercard: 5555 5555 5555 4444
  - Amex: 3782 822463 10005

  (Stripe maintains detailed testing card lists for various scenarios) [Testing - Stripe](https://docs.stripe.com/testing).

- To test SCA (3DS) and required authentication flows, use the 4000 0025 0000 3155 card and follow Stripe test scenarios [Testing - Stripe](https://docs.stripe.com/testing).

3) Webhook testing locally (Stripe CLI)

- Install and log in to the Stripe CLI; forward events to your local /webhook endpoint with:

  stripe listen --forward-to localhost:4242/webhook

- The CLI will print a webhook signing secret you can use as STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET during local testing (or use the CLI’s printed secret to configure your server) [Stripe CLI docs](https://docs.stripe.com/stripe-cli/use-cli) [Webhooks docs](https://docs.stripe.com/webhooks).

- You can trigger test webhooks via the CLI as well (e.g., stripe trigger payment_intent.succeeded) or create real test payments in the UI to generate events [Stripe CLI docs](https://docs.stripe.com/stripe-cli/use-cli).

4) End-to-end testing recommendations

- Use manual E2E tests with the Payment Element and test cards to validate client flows and authentication prompts.
- Mock or stub Stripe API responses in unit tests for server-side logic; for integration tests use test API keys.
- Validate webhook signature handling by replaying events and using the Stripe CLI to forward events to your local webhook endpoint [Automated testing guidance](https://docs.stripe.com/automated-testing) [Webhooks docs](https://docs.stripe.com/webhooks).

Common pitfalls and how to avoid them

- Exposing secret keys to the client: ensure only publishable keys are used in frontend builds; secret keys must remain server-side [Keys best practices](https://docs.stripe.com/keys-best-practices).
- Forgetting webhook signature verification: always verify with stripe.Webhook.construct_event and the STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET to avoid spoofed events [Webhooks docs](https://docs.stripe.com/webhooks).
- Using the wrong client_secret: when you create subscriptions you must expand latest_invoice.payment_intent and use that client_secret for the Payment Element confirm flow; using the subscription id alone will not allow Payment Element to finish initial payment [Build subscriptions with Elements](https://docs.stripe.com/payments/advanced/build-subscriptions).
- Not handling 3DS/Authentication flows: Payment Element + stripe.confirmPayment will handle authentication flows automatically if confirm is used with the elements instance and the client_secret; ensure return_url is set for redirect confirmation flows [Payment Element docs](https://docs.stripe.com/payments/payment-element) [React Stripe.js reference](https://stripe.com/docs/stripe-js/react).
- Misconfigured CORS or incorrect endpoints between client and server: ensure the frontend fetches the correct backend URL and that the backend is reachable (use same-origin or CORS configuration as needed).

Checklist before going live

- Replace test API keys with live keys from Dashboard [Set up your development environment - Stripe Documentation](https://docs.stripe.com/get-started/development-environment?lang=python).
- Confirm webhook endpoints in Stripe Dashboard and use the live webhook signing secret for verification [Configuring webhook endpoints](https://docs.stripe.com/webhooks/setup#configure-webhook-settings).
- Review keys and rotate/restrict as appropriate [Keys best practices](https://docs.stripe.com/keys-best-practices).

Quick links to relevant Stripe docs & samples (used throughout the playbook)

- Payment Element docs: https://docs.stripe.com/payments/payment-element
- React Stripe.js: https://stripe.com/docs/stripe-js/react
- Stripe samples (accept-a-payment payment-element): https://github.com/stripe-samples/accept-a-payment/tree/main/payment-element
- Webhooks: https://docs.stripe.com/webhooks
- Testing cards & scenarios: https://docs.stripe.com/testing
- Stripe CLI: https://docs.stripe.com/stripe-cli/use-cli
- Keys best practices: https://docs.stripe.com/keys-best-practices

Additional implementation notes

- The provided FastAPI code is ready to run after installing dependencies and populating environment variables; adapt the TODOs to persist orders/subscriptions in your database and reconcile webhook events with your internal records [accept-a-payment sample server/python main.py](https://github.com/stripe-samples/accept-a-payment/blob/main/payment-element/server/python/main.py) [Payment Element docs](https://docs.stripe.com/payments/payment-element).

- The React example uses the official @stripe/react-stripe-js components and stripe.confirmPayment as recommended for Payment Element integrations [React Stripe.js reference](https://stripe.com/docs/stripe-js/react).

Start testing now

- Add your test API keys to your environment, start the FastAPI server, run the React dev server, then use the Stripe CLI to forward webhooks and test one-time and subscription flows with the test card numbers above [Stripe CLI docs](https://docs.stripe.com/stripe-cli/use-cli) [Testing - Stripe](https://docs.stripe.com/testing).

